{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539301"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16568"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16568"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.74,0.03,0.16,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65718"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9259"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51157"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1456"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5931"},{"type":"tags","id":"7506"},{"type":"tags","id":"8067"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44971"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65718"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe vertigo that began three days ago following an upper respiratory tract infection. The vertigo is worse with head movement and is associated with nausea and vomiting. She reports difficulty walking due to imbalance. She has no hearing loss or tinnitus. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. There is horizontal nystagmus with the fast phase beating away from the affected side. She has a positive head impulse test and tends to fall towards the affected side when standing. Otoscopic examination and hearing are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Meniere disease","Vestibular neuritis","Acoustic neuroma","Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","Mal de debarquement syndrome"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of vestibular neuritis: acute onset severe vertigo following a viral illness, with signs of unilateral vestibular dysfunction but preserved hearing. The condition is thought to be caused by viral inflammation of the vestibular nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute severe vertigo lasting days, accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and postural imbalance. The head impulse test is positive, and there is horizontal nystagmus beating away from the affected side. Importantly, hearing is preserved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere disease\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by episodic vertigo lasting hours, accompanied by fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. These episodes recur over time. The absence of auditory symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcoustic neuroma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with gradual, progressive unilateral hearing loss and tinnitus, with or without balance problems. The acute onset and preserved hearing make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenign paroxysmal positional vertigo\u003C/strong\u003E causes brief episodes of vertigo (seconds) triggered by specific head positions. The vertigo in this case is constant and severe, which is inconsistent with BPPV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMal de debarquement syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a persistent sensation of rocking or swaying, typically following sea travel or other sustained motion exposure. The acute onset and preceding viral illness make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vestibular neuritis typically presents with acute severe vertigo following a viral illness.","Vestibular neuritis is characterised by unilateral vestibular loss, nystagmus, and postural imbalance without hearing loss.","Most cases of vestibular neuritis resolve spontaneously within weeks to months."],"references":["Bae CH, Na HG, Choi YS. Current diagnosis and treatment of vestibular neuritis: a narrative review. J Yeungnam Med Sci. 2022 Apr;39(2):81-88. doi: 10.12701/yujm.2021.01228. Epub 2021 Aug 9. PMID: 34411472; PMCID: PMC8913909.","Greco A, Macri GF, Gallo A, Fusconi M, De Virgilio A, Pagliuca G, Marinelli C, de Vincentiis M. Is vestibular neuritis an immune related vestibular neuropathy inducing vertigo? J Immunol Res. 2014;2014:459048. doi: 10.1155/2014/459048. Epub 2014 Jan 15. PMID: 24741601; PMCID: PMC3987789.","Jeong SH, Kim HJ, Kim JS. Vestibular neuritis. Semin Neurol. 2013 Jul;33(3):185-94. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1354598. Epub 2013 Sep 21. PMID: 24057821.","Bae CH, Na HG, Choi YS. Current diagnosis and treatment of vestibular neuritis: a narrative review. J Yeungnam Med Sci. 2022 Apr;39(2):81-88. doi: 10.12701/yujm.2021.01228. Epub 2021 Aug 9. PMID: 34411472; PMCID: PMC8913909."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51157"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16568"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51157"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T17:54:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T10:13:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9259"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65718"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"e